9:T5ed,<p>Mental models are representations of how the world works. They're the lenses you use to interpret situations, make decisions, and predict outcomes.</p>
<p>The goal isn't to have one perfect model — it's to have a rich collection so you can pick the right lens for the situation.</p>
<h2>My most-used models</h2>
<p><strong>First principles</strong> — Strip away assumptions. What is actually true here? What must be true for this to work? Separate facts from conventions.</p>
<p><strong>Inversion</strong> — Think about problems backwards. Instead of "how do I succeed," ask "what would guarantee failure?" Then avoid those things.</p>
<p><strong>Second-order effects</strong> — Every action has direct and indirect consequences. The indirect ones often dominate over time. Ask: "and then what?"</p>
<p><strong>Opportunity cost</strong> — Every choice is also a set of unchosen alternatives. The real cost of any decision includes what you gave up.</p>
<p><strong>Margin of safety</strong> — Build in buffers. The world is uncertain. Things take longer and cost more than you think. Plan for it.</p>
<h2>The meta-model</h2>
<p>The best mental model is one you can actually apply today. An elegant framework you can't use is just trivia.</p>
<p>Test every model you learn: "In what situation would I use this? What would I do differently because of it?"</p>
<p>Related: <a href="/notes/systems-thinking" class="wikilink">Systems Thinking</a>, <a href="/notes/leverage" class="wikilink">Leverage</a></p>
